{"title_page": "Fylde Ladies F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football club | \n| current  = \n| clubname = Fylde Ladies\n| image = File:Fylde Ladies logo.jpg\n| fullname = Fylde Ladies Football Club \n| nickname = \"The Coasters\"\n| founded = 1971 (as Duke of York)\n| disbanded = 28th April 2020\n| ground = Mill Farm, [[Wesham]]\n| league   = {{English football updater-W|Fylde}}\n|pattern_la1= |pattern_b1= |pattern_ra1= |leftarm1=FFFFFF |body1=FFFFFF |rightarm1=FFFFFF |shorts1=FFFFFF |socks1=FFFFFF\n|pattern_la2= |pattern_b2=_blackstripes_thin4 |pattern_ra2= |pattern_so2=_blacktop |pattern_sh2=_whitebottom|body2=FFFF00 |leftarm2=FFFF00 |rightarm2=FFFF00 |shorts2=000000 |socks2=FFFF00\n}}\n\n'''Fylde Ladies Football Club''' were an [[England|English]] [[Women's association football|women's football]] club affiliated with [[A.F.C. Fylde]] and up until their disbandment played in the {{English football updater-W|Fylde}}.\n\n==History==\nThe club was formed under the name '''Duke of York''' in 1971, as founder members of the North West Women's Football League. They were renamed '''Preston Rangers W.F.C.''' in 1977 and reached the semi finals of the [[FA Women's Cup]] in 1982\u201383 and 1989\u201390.\n\nIn 1997 they became '''Preston North End W.F.C.''' and finished 1997\u201398 as champions, winning promotion to the [[Northern Combination Women's Football League]]. In 1999 the club was officially affiliated with [[Preston North End F.C.]].\n\nThe club won the [[Northern Combination Women's Football League]] in 2005\u201306 and were promoted into the [[FA Women's Premier League Northern Division]] for the first time.\n\nIn June 2011 PNE appointed Luke Swindlehurst as the 1st Team Manager. This follows his previous role as Assistant Manager in the 2010/11 season.\n\nThe club was rebranded '''Fylde Ladies F.C.''' in May 2016 after switching its association from Preston North End to A.F.C. Fylde.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Agnew|first1=Daniel|title=PNE women's team have fresh start as Fylde Ladies|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/pne-women-s-team-have-fresh-start-as-fylde-ladies-1-7929437|accessdate=20 June 2016|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nDue to the Covid-19 global pandemic, on the 28th April 2020, the team was disbanded due to the growing uncertainties within the women\u2019s game, and the financial implications the pandemic had taken. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Wrack|first1=Suzy|title= AFC Fylde women\u2019s team disbanded after club takes \u2018tough decision\u2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/28/afc-fylde-womens-team-disbanded-after-club-takes-tough-decision|accessdate=28 April 2020|publisher=The Guardian|date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n{{updated|28 April 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Fylde Ladies 2018-19 squad|url=http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/fylde-ladies/|accessdate=3 February 2019|date=|publisher=[[A.F.C. Fylde]]}}</ref>\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player | no=1| nat=ENG | pos=GK | name= [[Brittany Jackson (footballer)|Brittany Jackson]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=2| nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Olivia Wild (footballer)|Olivia Wild]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=3| nat=WAL | pos=FW | name= [[Emily Hollinshead]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=4| nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Hannah Forster]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=5| nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Olivia Fuller (footballer)|Olivia Fuller]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=6| nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Jenna Carroll]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=7| nat=ENG | pos=FW | name= [[Danielle Young]]|other=[[captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=8| nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Hollie Kelsh]]}}\n{{fs player | no=10|nat=WAL | pos=FW | name= [[Alys Hinchcliffe]]}} \n{{Fs mid}}\n{{fs player | no=11|nat=NZL | pos=MF | name= [[Laura Merrin]]}} \n{{Fs player | no=12|nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Erin Staunton-Turner]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=13|nat=ENG | pos=GK | name= [[Jen Myler]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=14|nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Sasha Rowe]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=15|nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Chloe Rowe]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=16|nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Lucy Staunton-Turner]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=17|nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Megan Taylor (footballer)|Megan Taylor]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=18|nat=ENG | pos=FW | name= [[Nikki Berko]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=20|nat=WAL | pos=GK | name= [[Grace Burke]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=21|nat=NIR | pos=MF | name= [[Kim Turner (footballer)|Kim Turner]]}}\n{{fs player | no=  |nat=ENG | pos=FW | name= [[Georgia Stevens (footballer)|Georgia Stevens]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Retired numbers===\n{{main|Retired numbers in association football}}\n<big>'''19'''</big> {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Zoe Tynan]], [[Midfielder]] (2016)<ref>{{cite news|title=Zoe Tynan: Fylde Ladies FC retire midfielder's number 19 shirt|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37261207|accessdate=27 September 2016|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Coaching Staff ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!\n!Role\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Conrad Prendergast \n||| First Team Manager\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Daniel Whitworth\n||| Assistant Manager and Goalkeeper Coach\n|-\n|{{flagicon|NIR}} [[Kim Turner (footballer)|Kim Turner]] \n||| Strength and Fitness Coach\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} George Barnes\n||| Sports Therapist\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Alisa Cowen\n||| Media Officer\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Josh Brown and {{Flagicon|ENG}} Ross Conway\n||| Analysts\n|-\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://fulltime-league.thefa.com/Index.do?league=872938/ Fixtures and Results]\n*[http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/fylde-ladies/ Official website]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{A.F.C. Fylde}}\n{{Preston North End F.C.}}\n{{FA Women's Premier League}}\n{{Women's football in England}}\n{{City of Preston culture}}\n{{Borough of Fylde culture}}\n\n{{Coord|53.7973212|N|2.8899875|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:A.F.C. Fylde]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C.]]\n[[Category:Women's football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Sport in the Borough of Fylde]]\n[[Category:Sport in Preston]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:FA Women's National League teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football club | \n| current  = \n| clubname = Fylde Ladies\n| image = File:Fylde Ladies logo.jpg\n| fullname = Fylde Ladies Football Club \n| nickname = \"The Coasters\"\n| founded = 1971 (as Duke of York)\n| disbanded = 28th April 2020\n| ground = Mill Farm, [[Wesham]]\n| league   = {{English football updater-W|Fylde}}\n|pattern_la1= |pattern_b1= |pattern_ra1= |leftarm1=FFFFFF |body1=FFFFFF |rightarm1=FFFFFF |shorts1=FFFFFF |socks1=FFFFFF\n|pattern_la2= |pattern_b2=_blackstripes_thin4 |pattern_ra2= |pattern_so2=_blacktop |pattern_sh2=_whitebottom|body2=FFFF00 |leftarm2=FFFF00 |rightarm2=FFFF00 |shorts2=000000 |socks2=FFFF00\n}}\n\n'''Fylde Ladies Football Club''' were an [[England|English]] [[Women's association football|women's football]] club affiliated with [[A.F.C. Fylde]] and up until their disbandment played in the {{English football updater-W|Fylde}}.\n\n==History==\nThe club was formed under the name '''Duke of York''' in 1971, as founder members of the North West Women's Football League. They were renamed '''Preston Rangers W.F.C.''' in 1977 and reached the semi finals of the [[FA Women's Cup]] in 1982\u201383 and 1989\u201390.\n\nIn 1997 they became '''Preston North End W.F.C.''' and finished 1997\u201398 as champions, winning promotion to the [[Northern Combination Women's Football League]]. In 1999 the club was officially affiliated with [[Preston North End F.C.]].\n\nThe club won the [[Northern Combination Women's Football League]] in 2005\u201306 and were promoted into the [[FA Women's Premier League Northern Division]] for the first time.\n\nIn June 2011 PNE appointed Luke Swindlehurst as the 1st Team Manager. This follows his previous role as Assistant Manager in the 2010/11 season.\n\nThe club was rebranded '''Fylde Ladies F.C.''' in May 2016 after switching its association from Preston North End to A.F.C. Fylde.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Agnew|first1=Daniel|title=PNE women's team have fresh start as Fylde Ladies|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/pne-women-s-team-have-fresh-start-as-fylde-ladies-1-7929437|accessdate=20 June 2016|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nDue to the Covid-19 global pandemic, on the 28th April 2020, the team was disbanded due to the growing uncertainties within the women\u2019s game, and the financial implications the pandemic had taken. <ref>{{cite news|Last1=Wrack|first1=Suzy|title= AFC Fylde women\u2019s team disbanded after club takes \u2018tough decision\u2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/28/afc-fylde-womens-team-disbanded-after-club-takes-tough-decision|accessdate=28 April 2020|publisher=The Guardian|date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n{{updated|28 April 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Fylde Ladies 2018-19 squad|url=http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/fylde-ladies/|accessdate=3 February 2019|date=|publisher=[[A.F.C. Fylde]]}}</ref>\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player | no=1| nat=ENG | pos=GK | name= [[Brittany Jackson (footballer)|Brittany Jackson]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=2| nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Olivia Wild (footballer)|Olivia Wild]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=3| nat=WAL | pos=FW | name= [[Emily Hollinshead]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=4| nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Hannah Forster]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=5| nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Olivia Fuller (footballer)|Olivia Fuller]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=6| nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Jenna Carroll]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=7| nat=ENG | pos=FW | name= [[Danielle Young]]|other=[[captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=8| nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Hollie Kelsh]]}}\n{{fs player | no=10|nat=WAL | pos=FW | name= [[Alys Hinchcliffe]]}} \n{{Fs mid}}\n{{fs player | no=11|nat=NZL | pos=MF | name= [[Laura Merrin]]}} \n{{Fs player | no=12|nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Erin Staunton-Turner]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=13|nat=ENG | pos=GK | name= [[Jen Myler]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=14|nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Sasha Rowe]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=15|nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Chloe Rowe]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=16|nat=ENG | pos=DF | name= [[Lucy Staunton-Turner]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=17|nat=ENG | pos=MF | name= [[Megan Taylor (footballer)|Megan Taylor]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=18|nat=ENG | pos=FW | name= [[Nikki Berko]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=20|nat=WAL | pos=GK | name= [[Grace Burke]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=21|nat=NIR | pos=MF | name= [[Kim Turner (footballer)|Kim Turner]]}}\n{{fs player | no=  |nat=ENG | pos=FW | name= [[Georgia Stevens (footballer)|Georgia Stevens]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Retired numbers===\n{{main|Retired numbers in association football}}\n<big>'''19'''</big> {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Zoe Tynan]], [[Midfielder]] (2016)<ref>{{cite news|title=Zoe Tynan: Fylde Ladies FC retire midfielder's number 19 shirt|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37261207|accessdate=27 September 2016|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Coaching Staff ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!\n!Role\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Conrad Prendergast \n||| First Team Manager\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Daniel Whitworth\n||| Assistant Manager and Goalkeeper Coach\n|-\n|{{flagicon|NIR}} [[Kim Turner (footballer)|Kim Turner]] \n||| Strength and Fitness Coach\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} George Barnes\n||| Sports Therapist\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Alisa Cowen\n||| Media Officer\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ENG}} Josh Brown and {{Flagicon|ENG}} Ross Conway\n||| Analysts\n|-\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://fulltime-league.thefa.com/Index.do?league=872938/ Fixtures and Results]\n*[http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/fylde-ladies/ Official website]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{A.F.C. Fylde}}\n{{Preston North End F.C.}}\n{{FA Women's Premier League}}\n{{Women's football in England}}\n{{City of Preston culture}}\n{{Borough of Fylde culture}}\n\n{{Coord|53.7973212|N|2.8899875|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:A.F.C. Fylde]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C.]]\n[[Category:Women's football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Sport in the Borough of Fylde]]\n[[Category:Sport in Preston]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:FA Women's National League teams]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fylde_Ladies_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Patrick Meek", "text_new": "{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Patrick Meek\n| image          = Patrick Meek 2009 US Single Distance Championships.jpg\n| caption        = Patrick Meek accelerates during a race at the 2009 Single Distance National Championships\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1985|11|10}}\n| birth_place    = [[Evanston, Illinois]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| alma_mater     = [[University of Utah]]\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.patrickmeek.com}}\n| country        = {{USA}}\n| coach          = \n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Patrick Meek''' (born November 10, 1985) is American [[speed skater]] who represented the [[United States at the 2014 Winter Olympics|United States]] at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]]. Meek began speed skating at age two, following in the footsteps of his father and grandfather. After high school, he moved to [[Utah]] to further his speed skating career. He made the national team in 2006 and participated in the 2006 and 2010 Olympic Trials without success.\n\nMeek placed second in the 10,000 meters at the 2012\u20132013 National Championships. In 2013, he won two national titles taking the 25,000 and 50,000 meter events. In December, he placed third in the 5,000 meters at the Olympic Trials and thus qualified for his first Olympics. At the Olympics, Meek placed 20th in the 5,000 meters and 10th in the 10,000 meters after being added to the start list when other skaters withdrew.\n\n==Early life and education==\nPatrick Meek was born November 10, 1985 in the [[Chicago]] suburb of [[Evanston, Illinois]] into a family of avid speed skaters.<ref name=results /><ref name=Illinois />  His father was a speed skating coach and national team member, and his grandfather skated competitively at the club level. Meek's younger sister Kathleen also skated for a while, but gave up the sport as a kid.<ref name=distance />  By age two, basically as soon as he could walk, Meek was on speed skates learning the sport.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|title=Patrick Meek: US Speedskating|publisher=Team USA|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/ME/Patrick-Meek|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  He grew up in the Chicago suburbs before moving to [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]].<ref name=Illinois>{{cite news|title=Illinois dominates U.S. men's speedskating team|author=Jared S. Hopkins|date=December 31, 2013|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-12-31/sports/ct-speedskating-olympic-trials-spt-0101-20140101_1_winter-olympics-sochi-u-s-men|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=homepage />\n\nMeek graduated from high school in St. Louis in 2004 and moved to Utah to further his speed skating career. He earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Political Science]] from the [[University of Utah]] in 2009.<ref name=distance>{{cite web|title=Patrick Meek: Skating The Distance|author=Aimee Borg|date=December 20, 2013|publisher=Team USA|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Road-to-Sochi-2014/Features/2013/December/20/Patrick-Meek-Skating-The-Distance|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  As of 2014, he is working on a post-graduate degree at [[Ashworth College]].<ref name=profile />\n\n==Speed skating career==\nMeek made the national speed skating team in 2006.<ref name=homepage>{{cite web|title=PatrickMeek.com|url=http://patrickmeek.com/|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  He elected to pursue distance events, realizing he did not have the proper physical characteristics for sprints and was well suited psychologically for long races. At the 2006 Olympic Trials, Meek had no aspirations of making the team but turned in a personal best in the 10,000 meters. 2010 was a different story&nbsp;\u2013 Meek expected to make the team and was devastated when his personal best time came up short. \"At that moment, I [couldn't] get past the fact that I didn\u2019t make the Olympic team\", he later commented.  \"It was tough watching the event you\u2019d committed your life to [on TV].\"<ref name=distance />\n\nAt the 2012\u20132013 National Championships, Meek turned in a personal best time of 13:26.06 in the 10,000 meters en route to a second-place finish.<ref name=five />  In 2013, he won the United States title in the 25,000 and 50,000 meter races.<ref name=distance />  At the Olympic Trials in December, in the 5,000 meter race Meek had both contact lenses come out with 1.5 laps to go. As a result, he \"[couldn't] really see anything\" but got through the race with the help of his coach yelling encouragements.<ref name=roars />  He finished the race in 6:27.90, good enough for third place and a spot on the Olympic team. \"It was kind of frightening\", Meek recalled, but \"when you hear [your coach yell 'This is for the Olympic team!'], you think, \u2018Hey, I can do one more lap'\".<ref name=roars>{{cite news|title=Rookard Roars Back To Make Olympic Team|author=Karen Rosen|publisher=Team USA|date=December 28, 2013|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Road-to-Sochi-2014/Features/2013/December/28/Rookard-Roars-Back-To-Make-Olympic-Team|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  A few days later, Meek turned in a personal best time of 13:23.16 in the 10,000 meters, but came up 0.39 seconds short of the only qualifying spot in the event, placing third.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. teen earns second Olympic event at speedskating trials|work=USA Today|agency=AP|date=January 1, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/2014/01/01/emery-lehman-earns-second-sochi-olympics-event-usa-speedskating-trials/4282535/|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA the Olympics, Meek placed 20th in the 5000 meters with a time of 6:32.94. When several skaters from other nations withdrew from the 10,000 meters, Meek was selected from the alternate list to participate in the event. He finished the race in 13:28.72, placing 11th, five hundredths of a second behind Lehman. \"Honestly I just started laughing,\" Meek said of the difference. \"We were so close at trials and so close today.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Men's speed skating - 10,000-meters results|publisher=KSDK (Gannett)|work=USA Today|author=Kevin Oklobzija|url=http://www.ksdk.com/story/sports/olympics/2014/02/18/patrick-meek-netherlands-sweep-medals-speed-skating/5578877/|date=February 18, 2014|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDue to his difficult workouts, Meek has earned the nickname \"Mule.\"  He explains: \"I don't always look pretty out there&nbsp;... I am not the favorite barn animal. [But], more often than not, I get the job done out there.\"<ref name=five>{{cite news|title=Five athletes share their Olympic journey|publisher=ESPN|date=February 7, 2013|author=Sarah Spain|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/olympics/article/8926326/espnw-five-athletes-share-their-olympic-journey|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  Meek does a lot of extreme distance training (100+ laps at a time) which he says helps him in the 5,000 meter (12.5 laps) and 10,000 meter (25 laps) races.<ref name=distance />\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Patrick Meek 25000 & 50000 meter medals (2012).jpg|thumb|right|Meek won the 25000 meter and 50000 meter national championships in 2012]]\nAs part of a sponsorship deal, Meek works as a valet at the [[Waldorf Astoria Park City]] when not skating. In 2013, he teamed up with [[Charity: water]] to promote clean drinking water in the developing world. Meek also promotes [[Right To Play]], a charity formed by former speed skater [[Johann Olav Koss]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Speedskater aims to give back while chasing Olympic dream|author=Michael C. Lewis|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=December 24, 2013|url=http://m.sltrib.com/sltrib/mobile2/55519900-218/meek-charity-speedskating-olympic.html.csp|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  He has two sisters who live with his parents in [[Naples, Florida]].<ref name=homepage />\n\n==Personal bests==\n{{PersonalRecordsTop|ref=<ref name=results>{{cite web|url =http://www.speedskatingresults.com/index.php?p=17&s=3238|title = Patrick Meek|publisher  = SpeedSkatingResults.com|accessdate = January 4, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsSport|Men's speed skating}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|500 m|37.85|December 27, 2005|[[Utah Olympic Oval]], Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1000 m|1:13.36|March 8, 2008|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1500 m|1:49.38|December 31, 2013|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|3000 m|3:46.53|December 20, 2013|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|5000 m|6:19.86|January 12, 2012|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|10000 m|13:23.16|January 1, 2014|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsBottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.patrickmeek.com Personal website] of Patrick Meek\n*{{USOPC profile|ME/Patrick-Meek}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meek, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male speed skaters]]\n[[Category:Ashworth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of the United States]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:University of Utah alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Patrick Meek\n| image          = Patrick Meek 2009 US Single Distance Championships.jpg\n| caption        = Patrick Meek accelerates during a race at the 2009 Single Distance National Championships\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1985|11|10}}\n| birth_place    = [[Evanston, Illinois]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| alma_mater     = [[University of Utah]]\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.patrickmeek.com}}\n| country        = {{USA}}\n| coach          = \n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Patrick Meek''' (born November 10, 1985) is American [[speed skater]] who represented the [[United States at the 2014 Winter Olympics|United States]] at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]]. Meek began speed skating at age two, following in the footsteps of his father and grandfather. After high school, he moved to [[Utah]] to further his speed skating career. He made the national team in 2006 and participated in the 2006 and 2010 Olympic Trials without success.\n\nMeek placed second in the 10,000 meters at the 2012\u20132013 National Championships. In 2013, he won two national titles taking the 25,000 and 50,000 meter events. In December, he placed third in the 5,000 meters at the Olympic Trials and thus qualified for his first Olympics. At the Olympics, Meek placed 20th in the 5,000 meters and 10th in the 10,000 meters after being added to the start list when other skaters withdrew.\n\n==Early life and education==\nPatrick Meek was born November 10, 1985 in the [[Chicago]] suburb of [[Evanston, Illinois]] into a family of avid speed skaters.<ref name=results /><ref name=Illinois />  His father was a speed skating coach and national team member, and his grandfather skated competitively at the club level. Meek's younger sister Kathleen also skated for a while, but gave up the sport as a kid.<ref name=distance />  By age two, basically as soon as he could walk, Meek was on speed skates learning the sport.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|title=Patrick Meek: US Speedskating|publisher=Team USA|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/ME/Patrick-Meek|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  He grew up in the Chicago suburbs before moving to [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]].<ref name=Illinois>{{cite news|title=Illinois dominates U.S. men's speedskating team|author=Jared S. Hopkins|date=December 31, 2013|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-12-31/sports/ct-speedskating-olympic-trials-spt-0101-20140101_1_winter-olympics-sochi-u-s-men|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=homepage />\n\nMeek graduated from high school in St. Louis in 2004 and moved to Utah to further his speed skating career. He earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Political Science]] from the [[University of Utah]] in 2009.<ref name=distance>{{cite web|title=Patrick Meek: Skating The Distance|author=Aimee Borg|date=December 20, 2013|publisher=Team USA|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Road-to-Sochi-2014/Features/2013/December/20/Patrick-Meek-Skating-The-Distance|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  As of 2014, he is working on a post-graduate degree at [[Ashworth College]].<ref name=profile />\n\n==Speed skating career==\nMeek made the national speed skating team in 2006.<ref name=homepage>{{cite web|title=PatrickMeek.com|url=http://patrickmeek.com/|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  He elected to pursue distance events, realizing he did not have the proper physical characteristics for sprints and was well suited psychologically for long races. At the 2006 Olympic Trials, Meek had no aspirations of making the team but turned in a personal best in the 10,000 meters. 2010 was a different story&nbsp;\u2013 Meek expected to make the team and was devastated when his personal best time came up short. \"At that moment, I [couldn't] get past the fact that I didn\u2019t make the Olympic team\", he later commented.  \"It was tough watching the event you\u2019d committed your life to [on TV].\"<ref name=distance />\n\nAt the 2012\u20132013 National Championships, Meek turned in a personal best time of 13:26.06 in the 10,000 meters en route to a second-place finish.<ref name=five />  In 2013, he won the United States title in the 25,000 and 50,000 meter races.<ref name=distance />  At the Olympic Trials in December, in the 5,000 meter race Meek had both contact lenses come out with 1.5 laps to go. As a result, he \"[couldn't] really see anything\" but got through the race with the help of his coach yelling encouragements.<ref name=roars />  He finished the race in 6:27.90, good enough for third place and a spot on the Olympic team. \"It was kind of frightening\", Meek recalled, but \"when you hear [your coach yell 'This is for the Olympic team!'], you think, \u2018Hey, I can do one more lap'\".<ref name=roars>{{cite news|title=Rookard Roars Back To Make Olympic Team|author=Karen Rosen|publisher=Team USA|date=December 28, 2013|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Road-to-Sochi-2014/Features/2013/December/28/Rookard-Roars-Back-To-Make-Olympic-Team|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  A few days later, Meek turned in a personal best time of 13:23.16 in the 10,000 meters, but came up 0.39 seconds short of the only qualifying spot in the event, placing third.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. teen earns second Olympic event at speedskating trials|work=USA Today|agency=AP|date=January 1, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/2014/01/01/emery-lehman-earns-second-sochi-olympics-event-usa-speedskating-trials/4282535/|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA the Olympics, Meek placed 20th in the 5000 meters with a time of 6:32.94. When several skaters from other nations withdrew from the 10,000 meters, Meek was selected from the alternate list to participate in the event. He finished the race in 13:28.72, placing 11th, five hundredths of a second behind Lehman. \"Honestly I just started laughing,\" Meek said of the difference. \"We were so close at trials and so close today.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Men's speed skating - 10,000-meters results|publisher=KSDK (Gannett)|work=USA Today|author=Kevin Oklobzija|url=http://www.ksdk.com/story/sports/olympics/2014/02/18/patrick-meek-netherlands-sweep-medals-speed-skating/5578877/|date=February 18, 2014|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDue to his difficult workouts, Meek has earned the nickname \"Mule.\"  He explains: \"I don't always look pretty out there&nbsp;... I am not the favorite barn animal. [But], more often than not, I get the job done out there.\"<ref name=five>{{cite news|title=Five athletes share their Olympic journey|publisher=ESPN|date=February 7, 2013|author=Sarah Spain|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/olympics/article/8926326/espnw-five-athletes-share-their-olympic-journey|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  Meek does a lot of extreme distance training (100+ laps at a time) which he says helps him in the 5,000 meter (12.5 laps) and 10,000 meter (25 laps) races.<ref name=distance />\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Patrick Meek 25000 & 50000 meter medals (2012).jpg|thumb|right|Meek won the 25000 meter and 50000 meter national championships in 2012]]\nAs part of a sponsorship deal, Meek works as a valet at the [[Waldorf Astoria Park City]] when not skating. In 2013, he teamed up with [[Charity: water]] to promote clean drinking water in the developing world. Meek also promotes [[Right To Play]], a charity formed by former speed skater [[Johann Olav Koss]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Speedskater aims to give back while chasing Olympic dream|author=Michael C. Lewis|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=December 24, 2013|url=http://m.sltrib.com/sltrib/mobile2/55519900-218/meek-charity-speedskating-olympic.html.csp|accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>  He has two sisters who live with his parents in [[Naples, Florida]].<ref name=homepage />\n\n==Personal bests==\n{{PersonalRecordsTop|ref=<ref name=results>{{cite web|url =http://www.speedskatingresults.com/index.php?p=17&s=3238|title = Patrick Meek|publisher  = SpeedSkatingResults.com|accessdate = January 4, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsSport|Men's speed skating}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|500 m|37.85|December 27, 2005|[[Utah Olympic Oval]], Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1000 m|1:13.36|March 8, 2008|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1500 m|1:49.38|December 31, 2013|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|3000 m|3:46.53|December 20, 2013|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|5000 m|6:19.86|January 12, 2012|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|10000 m|13:23.16|January 1, 2014|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsBottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.patrickmeek.com Personal website] of Patrick Meek\n*[http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/ME/Patrick-Meek Official profile] at Team USA website\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meek, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male speed skaters]]\n[[Category:Ashworth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of the United States]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:University of Utah alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "use template for USOPC link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Meek"}
{"title_page": "Hand clasping", "text_new": "[[File:William J. Clinton - NCI Visuals Online.jpg|thumb|220px|'''''L''''' [[phenotype]] of hand clasping<br>([[Bill Clinton]])]]\n'''Hand clasping''' is the superposition of each [[finger]] of one [[hand]] over the corresponding finger of the opposite hand. When clasping the hands, a person tends to interlace the fingers in one of two ways. People who hold the fingers of the right hand above the left fingers are classified as [[phenotype]] ''R'' (right), while those who hold the fingers of the left hand above those of the right are phenotype ''L'' (left).\n\nAlthough some people do not exhibit a preference for one type of hand clasping, most do. Once adopted, the method of hand clasping tends to be consistent throughout life. When an individual attempts to clasp the hands in the opposite configuration from the usual one, that person may feel a sense that something is out of the ordinary.\n\nIt was noted that the ''R'' type occurs more frequently in women than in men, which led to popular speculation that all persons with ''L'' phenotype are more emotional than persons with ''R'' type.{{Dubious|date=February 2016}}<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 4461659 | doi=10.1159/000152670 | volume=24 | title=Preferences for handedness, arm folding, and hand clasping in families | year=1974 | journal=Hum Hered | pages=345\u201351  | last1 = Ferronato | first1 = S | last2 = Thomas | first2 = D | last3 = Sadava | first3 = D}}</ref>\n\nLai and Walsh (1965) suspect that [[genotype|genetic factors]] are important in determining these characteristics. They looked at a sample of 18 families.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 5836191 | volume=37 | title=The patterns of hand clasping in different ethnic groups | year=1965 | journal=Hum Biol | pages=312\u20139  | last1 = Lai | first1 = LY | last2 = Walsh | first2 = RJ}}</ref>\n\nBased on the comparison of a series of monozygotic and dizygotic [[twins]], Freire-Maia (1961) concluded that the preference in the type of hand clasping was affected by certain genetic factors, and (perhaps) to a significant extent.<ref>Freire-Maia A. (1961): Twin data on hand clasping: a reanalysis. Acta Genet. Statist. Med. 10: 207-211.</ref>\n\nFalk and Ayala (1971) found a significant correlation between parent-offspring and for this feature suggested model polygenic inheritance.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Falk | first1 = C. T. | last2 = Ayala | first2 = F. J. | year = 1971 | title = Genetic aspects of arm folding and hand clasping. | url = | journal = Jpn. J. Hum. Genet | volume = 15 | issue = | pages = 241\u2013247 }}</ref>\n\nMartin (1975) presented the results of studies of [[twins]] and found that genetic factors are still determining the phenotypic expression of this trait.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Martin | first1 = N. G | year = 1975 | title = No evidence for a genetic basis of tongue rolling or hand clasping | url = | journal = J. Hered | volume = 66 | issue = | pages = 179\u2013180 | pmid = 1236879 | doi = 10.1093/oxfordjournals.jhered.a108608 }}</ref>\n\nReiss (1999) found that 55% of the [[population]] belongs to the phenotype ''L'', and 44% have a \"right type\" clasping; the remaining 1% did not care.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pons | first1 = J | year = 1961 | title = Hand clasping | url = | journal = Ann. Hum. Genet | volume = 25 | issue = | pages = 141\u2013144 | pmid = 14487797 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-1809.1961.tb01511.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Reiss | first1 = M | year = 1999 | title = The genetics of hand-clasping-a review and a familial study | url = | journal = Ann. Hum. Biol. | volume = 26 | issue = | pages = 39\u201348 | pmid = 9974082 | doi = 10.1080/030144699282967 }}</ref>\n\nIn support of the hypothesis about the significant influence of genetic factors on the [[phenotype|phenotypic expression]] of the extreme [[Polymorphism (biology)|dimorphism]] clearly demarcated by the data on a very wide range of variation in the frequency of phenotypes tested parts of the world's population.{{confusing-inline|date=July 2019}}\n\n==''R'' phenotype distribution==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"toccolours\" 0.5em solid #999; 100%\n|- \n|  style=\"background:#dfd; \"|'''Population'''\n|  style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|'''N''' \n|'''R''' (%)\n|style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|References\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Belgium]] \n|644      \n|48.1     \n|Leguebe (1967)<ref>Leguebe  1967  hand clasping:  \u00e9tude anthropologique et g\u00e9n\u00e9tique. Bull. Soc. Roy. Antrop. Pr\u00e9hist., 78: 81-107.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\" | [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]  \n|10,073    \n|55.1   \n|Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1979)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 | first1 = R. | last2 = Berberovi\u0107 | first2 = Lj. | last3 = Sofrad\u017eija | first3 = A. | year = 1979 | title = Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine | url = | journal = God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu | volume = 32 | issue = | pages = 101\u2013116 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Bulgaria]]  \n|?   \n|70.1 \n| Boev, Todorov (1970)<ref>Boev, Todorov, 1970,  in: Gavrilovi\u0107 \u017d., Bo\u017ei\u0107 V. (1972): Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini. ''Genetika'', 4 (1): 59-61.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Greece]]  \n|?        \n|81.2    \n|Pelecanos (1969)<ref>Pelecanos 1969,  in:   Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Poland]]   \n|771  \n| 48.0   \n| Wolanski et al. (1973)<ref>Wolanski et al 1973, in:  Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Scotland]]     \n|598  \n|60.0\n| Lutz (1908)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Lutz | first1 = F. E. | year = 1908 | title = The inheritance of the manner of clasping the hands | url = | journal = Am. Nat. | volume = 42 | issue = | pages = 195\u2013196 | doi = 10.1086/278920 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Serbia]]: [[U\u017eice]]  \n|2,217    \n|54.0   \n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al.(1979)<ref>Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R., Berberovi\u0107 Lj., Sofrad\u017eija A. (1979): Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine. God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu, 32: 101-116.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Serbia]]:  [[Voivodina]]   \n|2,686      \n|51.9  \n|Gavrilovi\u0107, Bo\u017ei\u0107 (1972)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gavrilovi\u0107 | first1 = \u017d. | last2 = Bo\u017ei\u0107 | first2 = V. | year = 1972 | title = Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini | url = | journal = Genetika | volume = 4 | issue = 1| pages = 59\u201361 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Spain]]     \n|486    \n|52.1     \n|Pons (1961)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pons | first1 = J | year = 1961 | title = Hand clasping (Spanish data) | url = | journal = Ann. Hum. Genet. | volume = 25 | issue = | pages = 141\u2013144 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-1809.1961.tb01511.x | pmid = 14487797 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Sweden]]    \n|981    \n|52.1    \n|Beckman,  Elston (1962)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Beckman | first1 = L. Elston R. | year = 1962 | title = Data on bilateral variations in man: handedness, hand clasping and arm folding in Swedes | url = | journal = Hum. Biol. | volume = 34 | issue = | pages = 99\u2013103 }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arm folding]]\n*[[Hand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/inheritance/observable/ (en)\n\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Classical genetics]]\n[[Category:Human population genetics]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:William J. Clinton - NCI Visuals Online.jpg|thumb|220px|'''''L''''' [[phenotype]] of hand clasping<br>([[Bill Clinton]])]]\n'''Hand clasping''' is the superposition of each [[finger]] of one [[hand]] over the corresponding finger of the opposite hand. When clasping the hands, a person tends to interlace the fingers in one of two ways. People who hold the fingers of the right hand above the left fingers are classified as [[phenotype]] ''R'' (right), while those who hold the fingers of the left hand above those of the right are phenotype ''L'' (left).\n\nAlthough some people do not exhibit a preference for one type of hand clasping, most do. Once adopted, the method of hand clasping tends to be consistent throughout life. When an individual attempts to clasp the hands in the opposite configuration from the usual one, that person may feel a sense that something is out of the ordinary.\n\nIt was noted that the ''R'' type occurs more frequently in women than in men, which led to popular speculation that all persons with ''L'' phenotype are more emotional than persons with ''R'' type.{{Dubious|date=February 2016}}<ref>Ferronato S., Thomas D., Sadava D. (1974): Preferences for handedness, arm folding, and hand clasping in families. Hum. Hered., 24: 345-351,[PubMed: 4461659, related citations]</ref>\n\nLai and Walsh (1965) suspect that [[genotype|genetic factors]] are important in determining these characteristics. They looked at a sample of 18 families.<ref>Lai L. Y. C., Walsh R. J. (1965): The patterns of hand clasping in different ethnic groups. Hum. Biol. 37: 312-319.[PubMed: 5836191, related citations]</ref>\n\nBased on the comparison of a series of monozygotic and dizygotic [[twins]], Freire-Maia (1961) concluded that the preference in the type of hand clasping was affected by certain genetic factors, and (perhaps) to a significant extent.<ref>Freire-Maia A. (1961): Twin data on hand clasping: a reanalysis. Acta Genet. Statist. Med. 10: 207-211.</ref>\n\nFalk and Ayala (1971) found a significant correlation between parent-offspring and for this feature suggested model polygenic inheritance.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Falk | first1 = C. T. | last2 = Ayala | first2 = F. J. | year = 1971 | title = Genetic aspects of arm folding and hand clasping. | url = | journal = Jpn. J. Hum. Genet | volume = 15 | issue = | pages = 241\u2013247 }}</ref>\n\nMartin (1975) presented the results of studies of [[twins]] and found that genetic factors are still determining the phenotypic expression of this trait.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Martin | first1 = N. G | year = 1975 | title = No evidence for a genetic basis of tongue rolling or hand clasping | url = | journal = J. Hered | volume = 66 | issue = | pages = 179\u2013180 | pmid = 1236879 | doi = 10.1093/oxfordjournals.jhered.a108608 }}</ref>\n\nReiss (1999) found that 55% of the [[population]] belongs to the phenotype ''L'', and 44% have a \"right type\" clasping; the remaining 1% did not care.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pons | first1 = J | year = 1961 | title = Hand clasping | url = | journal = Ann. Hum. Genet | volume = 25 | issue = | pages = 141\u2013144 | pmid = 14487797 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-1809.1961.tb01511.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Reiss | first1 = M | year = 1999 | title = The genetics of hand-clasping-a review and a familial study | url = | journal = Ann. Hum. Biol. | volume = 26 | issue = | pages = 39\u201348 | pmid = 9974082 | doi = 10.1080/030144699282967 }}</ref>\n\nIn support of the hypothesis about the significant influence of genetic factors on the [[phenotype|phenotypic expression]] of the extreme [[Polymorphism (biology)|dimorphism]] clearly demarcated by the data on a very wide range of variation in the frequency of phenotypes tested parts of the world's population.{{confusing-inline|date=July 2019}}\n\n==''R'' phenotype distribution==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"toccolours\" 0.5em solid #999; 100%\n|- \n|  style=\"background:#dfd; \"|'''Population'''\n|  style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|'''N''' \n|'''R''' (%)\n|style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|References\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Belgium]] \n|644      \n|48.1     \n|Leguebe (1967)<ref>Leguebe  1967  hand clasping:  \u00e9tude anthropologique et g\u00e9n\u00e9tique. Bull. Soc. Roy. Antrop. Pr\u00e9hist., 78: 81-107.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\" | [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]  \n|10,073    \n|55.1   \n|Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1979)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 | first1 = R. | last2 = Berberovi\u0107 | first2 = Lj. | last3 = Sofrad\u017eija | first3 = A. | year = 1979 | title = Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine | url = | journal = God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu | volume = 32 | issue = | pages = 101\u2013116 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Bulgaria]]  \n|?   \n|70.1 \n| Boev, Todorov (1970)<ref>Boev, Todorov, 1970,  in: Gavrilovi\u0107 \u017d., Bo\u017ei\u0107 V. (1972): Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini. ''Genetika'', 4 (1): 59-61.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Greece]]  \n|?        \n|81.2    \n|Pelecanos (1969)<ref>Pelecanos 1969,  in:   Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Poland]]   \n|771  \n| 48.0   \n| Wolanski et al. (1973)<ref>Wolanski et al 1973, in:  Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Scotland]]     \n|598  \n|60.0\n| Lutz (1908)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Lutz | first1 = F. E. | year = 1908 | title = The inheritance of the manner of clasping the hands | url = | journal = Am. Nat. | volume = 42 | issue = | pages = 195\u2013196 | doi = 10.1086/278920 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Serbia]]: [[U\u017eice]]  \n|2,217    \n|54.0   \n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al.(1979)<ref>Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R., Berberovi\u0107 Lj., Sofrad\u017eija A. (1979): Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine. God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu, 32: 101-116.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Serbia]]:  [[Voivodina]]   \n|2,686      \n|51.9  \n|Gavrilovi\u0107, Bo\u017ei\u0107 (1972)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gavrilovi\u0107 | first1 = \u017d. | last2 = Bo\u017ei\u0107 | first2 = V. | year = 1972 | title = Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini | url = | journal = Genetika | volume = 4 | issue = 1| pages = 59\u201361 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Spain]]     \n|486    \n|52.1     \n|Pons (1961)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pons | first1 = J | year = 1961 | title = Hand clasping (Spanish data) | url = | journal = Ann. Hum. Genet. | volume = 25 | issue = | pages = 141\u2013144 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-1809.1961.tb01511.x }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Sweden]]    \n|981    \n|52.1    \n|Beckman,  Elston (1962)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Beckman | first1 = L. Elston R. | year = 1962 | title = Data on bilateral variations in man: handedness, hand clasping and arm folding in Swedes | url = | journal = Hum. Biol. | volume = 34 | issue = | pages = 99\u2013103 }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arm folding]]\n*[[Hand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/inheritance/observable/ (en)\n\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Classical genetics]]\