{"title_page": "Utroya River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name              =Utroya<br />{{lang-ru|\u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f}}<br />{{lang-lv|R\u012btupe}}\n| image             =R\u012btupe pie K\u0101rsavas 2000-07-22.jpg\n| image_size        =<!--Optional; defaults to 288 px-->\n| image_caption     =\n| source1_location  =[[Lake Meir\u0101nu]]\n| mouth             = [[Velikaya River|Velikaya]]\n| mouth_location    = \n| mouth_coordinates = {{coord|57|22|27|N|28|11|20|E|region:RU_type:waterbody_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=it}}\n| progression       = {{RVelikaya}}\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 =[[Latvia]], [[Russia]]\n| length            ={{convert|176|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"register\"/>\n| source1_elevation =\n| mouth_elevation   ={{convert|138|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg    ={{convert|17.2|m3/s|abbr=on}}<ref name=bse/>\n| basin_size        ={{convert|3000|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"register\"/>\n}}\nThe '''Utroya''' ({{lang-ru|\u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f}}, in Latvian the '''R\u012btupe''') is a river of [[Latvia]] and [[Pytalovsky District|Pytalovsky]] and [[Ostrovsky District, Pskov Oblast|Ostrovsky District]]s of [[Pskov Oblast]] of [[Russia]], a left tributary of the [[Velikaya River]]. It is {{convert|176|km|mi}} long, and the area of its basin {{convert|3000|km2|sqmi}}.<ref name=\"register\">{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=150017|script-title=ru:\u0420\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f (\u0420\u0438\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0435)|publisher=State Water Register of Russia|language=Russian|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> Its average discharge at 11 km from its mouth is {{convert|17.2|m3/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=bse>[http://bse.sci-lib.com/article114853.html \u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f], [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]</ref> The principal tributary is the [[Lzha River|Lzha]] (the Ludza, right). The towns of [[K\u0101rsava]] and [[Pytalovo]] are located on the banks of the R\u012btupe/Utroya.\n\nThe source of the R\u012btupe is [[Lake Meir\u0101nu]] in the lake district south of the town of K\u0101rsava. The river flows north, passes {{convert|2|km|mi}} from the center of Karsava, at a short stretch makes the state border between Latvia and Russia, and crosses into the Russian territory, to Pytalovsky District of Pskov Oblast. The official name of the river in Russia is the Utroya. The river further flows northwest, passes the town of Pytalovo, crosses into Ostrovsky District, accepts the Lzha from the right, and turns north. The mouth of the Utroya is in the village of [[Larino, Pskov Oblast|Larino]].\n\nThe [[drainage basin]] of the Utroya includes areas in the northeastern Latvia, as well as almost whole Pytalovsky District, the western part of Ostrovsky District, as well as minor areas in the western part of [[Krasnogorodsky District]] of [[Pskov Oblast]] in Russia.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Utroya}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Latvia]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Pskov Oblast]]\n[[Category:Latvia\u2013Russia border]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name              =Utroya<br />{{lang-ru|\u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f}}<br />{{lang-lv|R\u012btupe}}\n| image             =R\u012btupe pie K\u0101rsavas 2000-07-22.jpg\n| image_size        =<!--Optional; defaults to 288 px-->\n| image_caption     =\n| source1_location  =[[Lake Meir\u0101nu]]\n| mouth             = [[Velikaya River|Velikaya]]\n| mouth_location    = \n| mouth_coordinates = {{coord|57|22|27|N|28|11|20|E|region:RU_type:waterbody_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=it}}\n| progression       = {{RVelikaya}}\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 =[[Latvia]], [[Russia]]\n| length            ={{convert|176|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"register\"/>\n| source1_elevation =\n| mouth_elevation   ={{convert|138|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg    ={{convert|17.2|m3/s|abbr=on}}<ref name=bse/>\n| basin_size        ={{convert|3000|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"register\"/>\n}}\nThe '''Utroya''' ({{lang-ru|\u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f}}, in Latvian the '''R\u012btupe''') is a river of [[Latvia]] and [[Pytalovsky District|Pytalovsky]] and [[Ostrovsky District, Pskov Oblast|Ostrovsky District]]s of [[Pskov Oblast]] of [[Russia]], a left tributary of the [[Velikaya River]]. It is {{convert|176|km|mi}} long, and the area of its basin {{convert|3000|km2|sqmi}}.<ref name=\"register\">{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=150017|script-title=ru:\u0420\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f (\u0420\u0438\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0435)|publisher=State Water Register of Russia|language=Russian|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> Its average discharge at 11 km from its mouth is {{convert|17.2|m3/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=bse>[http://bse.sci-lib.com/article114853.html \u0423\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f], [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]</ref> The principal tributary is the [[Lzha River|Lzha]] (the Ludza, right). The towns of [[K\u0101rsava]] and [[Pytalovo]] are located on the banks of the R\u012btupe/Utroya.\n\nThe source of the R\u012btupe is [[Lake Meir\u0101nu]] in the lake district south of the town of K\u0101rsava. The river flows north, passes {{convert|2|km|mi}} from the center of Karsava, at a short stretch makes the state border between Latvia and Russia, and crosses into the Russian territory, to Pytalovsky District of Pskov Oblast. The official name of the river in Russia is the Utroya. The river further flows northwest, passes the town of Pytalovo, crosses into Ostrovsky District, accepts the Lzha from the right, and turns north. The mouth of the Utroya is in the village of [[Larino, Pskov Oblast|Larino]].\n\nThe [[drainage basin]] of the Utroya includes areas in the northeastern Latvia, as well as almost whole Pytalkovsky District, the western part of Ostrovsky District, as well as minor areas in the western part of [[Krasnogorodsky District]] of [[Pskov Oblast]] in Russia.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Utroya}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Latvia]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Pskov Oblast]]\n[[Category:Latvia\u2013Russia border]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utroya_River"}
{"title_page": "Bandcamp", "text_new": "{{for|band practice camps|band camp}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name       = Bandcamp, Inc.\n| logo       = Bandcamp-logotype-color.svg\n| logo_size  = 250px\n| screenshot = \n| type       = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry   = Music streaming, music purchasing\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2008|9|16}}\n| location   = [[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n| founder    = {{Unbulleted list |Ethan Diamond|Shawn Grunberger|Joe Holt|Neal Tucker}}\n| key_people = Ethan Diamond ([[CEO]])<br />Shawn Grunberger ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| alexa = {{DecreasePositive}} 974 ({{as of|2020|2|10|alt=February 2020}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/bandcamp.com |title= Bandcamp.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate= April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| homepage   = {{URL|https://bandcamp.com}}\n}}\n'''Bandcamp''' is an American [[Dot-com company|online]] [[music]] company founded in 2008 by [[Oddpost]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Baio|first= Andy |publisher = Maxy |title= Oddpost Co-Founder Launches Bandcamp, Publishing Platform for Musicians|url= http://waxy.org/2008/09/bandcamp_launch/ |accessdate=28 December 2013|date= Sep 16, 2008}}</ref> co-founder Ethan Diamond and programmers Shawn Grunberger, Joe Holt and Neal Tucker;<ref>{{cite news |last=John|first=Tozzi|title= Helping Indie Musicians Market Their Tunes|url= http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/helping-indie-musicians-market-their-tunes-11172011.html |accessdate=28 December 2013|newspaper=Business Week|date= November 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Private Company Financial Report on Bandcamp, Inc. |publisher= PrivCo |url= http://www.privco.com/private-company/bandcamp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sam|first= Clearman|title=An interview with Joe Holt|url= http://htmltimes.com/band-camp.php | work =The HTML Times|accessdate=28 December 2013 |date= October 1, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Ethan |first= Maffey|title=The Best of Bandcamp: Get in on the ground floor with these sell-it-yourself bands|url=http://www.bendsource.com/bend/the-best-of-bandcamp-get-in-on-the-ground-floor-with-these-sell-it-yourself-bands/Content?oid=2178549| work =The Source Weekly|accessdate=28 December 2013 |date= July 18, 2012 |quote= Web developers and friends Ethan Diamond, Shawn Grunberger, Joe Holt and Neal Tucker launched Bandcamp in 2008}}</ref> the company is headquartered in [[Oakland, California]].<ref name= kqed>{{cite web|accessdate= February 6, 2019|url= https://www.kqed.org/arts/13848866/inside-bandcamp-oakland-online-music-retailers-new-venue-record-shop-and-office|title=Inside Bandcamp's New Oakland Venue, Record Shop and Office|first=Sam |last=Lefebvre|publicationdate=January 17, 2019 |publisher= [[KQED]]|url-status= live |archivedate=May 21, 2019 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20190521010107/https://www.kqed.org/arts/13848866/inside-bandcamp-oakland-online-music-retailers-new-venue-record-shop-and-office}}</ref>\n\n==Model==\nArtists and labels upload music to Bandcamp and control how they sell it, setting their own prices, offering fans the option to pay more<ref>{{cite web |title=Bandcamp Help |url=https://bandcamp.com/help/selling#pricing_performance |website=Bandcamp |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> and selling merchandise.  \n\nFans are able to download their purchases or stream their music on the Bandcamp app/site only once or unlimited times by preserving the purchase voucher. They can also send purchased music as a gift,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.bandcamp.com/2013/11/26/thank-you-its-a-gift/ |title=Thank You, It\u2019s a Gift |work=The Bandcamp Blog |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref> view lyrics, and save individual songs or albums to a wish list. Uploading music to Bandcamp is free, and the company takes a 15% cut of sales made from their website (in addition to [[payment processor|payment processing]] fees), which drops to 10% after an artist's sales surpass $5000.<ref>{{cite news |author=James Shotwell |date=2010-06-20 |title=Bandcamp.com changes business model |publisher=Alt Press |url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/bandcamp.com_changes_business_model/ }}</ref>\n\nDownloads are offered both in [[Lossy audio compression|lossy formats]] as [[MP3]] (320k or V0), [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]] and [[Ogg Vorbis]] and in lossless formats as [[FLAC]], [[Apple Lossless Audio Codec|ALAC]], [[WAV]] and [[AIFF]]. <ref>{{Citation|url=https://get.bandcamp.help/hc/en-us/articles/360009319033-In-which-formats-can-I-download-my-purchases-|title=Bandcamp - In which formats can I download my purchases|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref> In addition to digital downloads artists may offer the purchase of their music on physical media such as [[Audio CD|CD]] or [[Vinyl record|vinyl]].\n\nBandcamp\u2019s website offers users access to an artist\u2019s page featuring information on the artist, social media links, merchandising links and listing their available music. Artists can change the look of their page, and to customize its features.<ref>{{cite web|last=Deitz |first=Ben |url=http://www.switched.com/2011/01/24/bandcamp-review-music-publishing-sharing-site/ |title=Bandcamp Decoded: An Indie Musician's Best (and Most Profitable) Friend |publisher=Switched.com |date=2011-01-24 |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref> In 2010 the site enabled embedded/shared links in other social media sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.bandcamp.com/2010/09/09/full-tracklist-players-facebook-love/ |title=Full Tracklist Players, Facebook Love |publisher=The Bandcamp Blog |date= |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref>\n\n==Notable artists and labels==\nBandcamp gained much attention in July 2010 when [[Amanda Palmer]], Low Places and Bedhed gave up their [[record label]]s and started selling albums on Bandcamp, using [[Twitter]] for promotion.<ref>{{cite news |author=Caroline Klibanoff |date=2010-07-27 |title=Amanda Palmer Brings in $15,000 on Bandcamp in Three Minutes |publisher=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]] |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2010/07/amanda-palmer-sells-15k-on-bandcampin-three-minute.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Glenn Peoples |date=2010-06-22 |title=Amanda Palmer Sells $15K Worth Of Music, Merch In Three Min |publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.biz]] |url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3ic0d7c3a6d02f0164fdfba6f2c15d432c }}</ref>\n\nSeveral [[indie game]] [[List of indie game developers|developers]] published their game soundtracks on Bandcamp,{{when|date=March 2020}} including the creators of ''[[Aquaria (video game)|Aquaria]]'', ''[[Bastion (video game)|Bastion]]'', ''[[Sanctum (2011 video game)|Sanctum]]'', ''[[Machinarium]]'', ''[[Terraria]]'', ''[[Plants vs. Zombies]]'', ''[[Limbo (video game)|Limbo]]'', ''[[Super Meat Boy]]'', ''[[To the Moon]]'', ''[[Fez (video game)|Fez]]'', and ''[[Minecraft]]''.{{importance inline}}\n\nIn December 2014, Bandcamp for Labels was launched. Popular independent labels such as [[Sub Pop]], [[Fat Wreck Chords]], [[Relapse Records]] and [[Epitaph Records]] launched their own Bandcamp pages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riffyou.com/fat-wreck-epitaph-sub-pop-get-bandcamp-pages/ |title=Fat Wreck, Epitaph, Sub-Pop Get Bandcamp Pages |publisher=Riffyou.com |date=December 17, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-18}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Peter Gabriel]] added his complete solo catalog to Bandcamp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/features/peter-gabriel-bandcamp-catalog|title=Peter Gabriel\u2019s Solo Discography Comes to Bandcamp|date=2019-11-15|website=Bandcamp Daily|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==''Bandcamp Daily''==\nIn the summer of 2016, the company launched '''''Bandcamp Daily''''', an online music publication which expanded its editorial content and offers articles about artists on the platform.<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|accessdate=May 20, 2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/20/arts/music/bandcamp-shopping-for-music.html|title=Is Bandcamp the Holy Grail of Online Record Stores?|first=Ben |last=Ratliff|authorlink=Ben Ratliff|publicationdate=August 19, 2016|website=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archivedate=August 19, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819230822/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/20/arts/music/bandcamp-shopping-for-music.html}}</ref><ref name=complex>{{cite web|accessdate=May 21, 2019|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/musicians-earned-270-million-dollars-from-bandcamp-last-year|title=Musicians Earned Over $270 Million From Bandcamp Last Year|first=Tara |last=Mahadevan|publicationdate=February 14, 2018|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|url-status=live|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20190521080822/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/musicians-earned-270-million-dollars-from-bandcamp-last-year}}</ref> The publication is based in New York.<ref name=kqed/> Its managing editor is Jes Skolnik, a writer for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'', as well as former author of [[punk zine]]s.<ref name=glamour>{{cite web|accessdate=May 21, 2019|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/career-late-bloomers|website=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|title=It's OK If You Don't Have Your Career Figured Out by 30|first=Maggie |last=Serota|publicationdate=November 10, 2017|url-status=live|archivedate=November 11, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111012741/https://www.glamour.com/story/career-late-bloomers}}</ref> Among ''Bandcamp Daily'''s columnists there have been writers of ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'',<ref>https://truthout.org/articles/outsourcing-police-investigations-to-google-risks-privacy-and-justice/</ref> ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'',<ref>https://www.inc.com/author/zachary-lipez</ref> [[NPR Music]],<ref>https://www.leafly.com/news/podcasts/subscribe-to-the-hash-podcast-new-season-begins-january-8th</ref> ''Pitchfork''<ref>https://theoutline.com/post/6013/dennis-cooper-very-intriguing-person</ref> and ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''.<ref>https://www.factmag.com/2018/08/08/fact-rated-channel-tres-interview/</ref> \n\nOn August 4, 2017, the staff of ''Bandcamp Daily'' donated all the sales proceeds from the day to the [[Transgender Law Center]], a civil rights organization for [[transgender]] people.<ref name=pitchfork>{{cite web|accessdate=May 21, 2019|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bandcamp-donating-proceeds-to-transgender-law-center-this-friday/|first=Sam|last=Sodomsky|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|publicationdate=July 31, 2017|title=Bandcamp Donating Proceeds to Transgender Law Center This Friday|url-status=live|archivedate=July 31, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731173711/https://pitchfork.com/news/bandcamp-donating-proceeds-to-transgender-law-center-this-friday/}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, the audience of ''Bandcamp Daily'' had increased by 84% since last year.<ref name=complex/><ref name=billboard>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8099603/bandcamp-paid-270-million-musicians-over-2017-review|accessdate=May 20, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=Bandcamp Paid Musicians Over $70M in 2017|publicationdate=February 13, 2018|first=Colin |last=Stutz |url-status=live|archivedate=February 14, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214043954/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8099603/bandcamp-paid-270-million-musicians-over-2017-review}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{citeweb | url = https://daily.bandcamp.com | title = Bandcamp Daily}}\n\n{{Music digital distribution platforms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandcamp}}\n[[Category:2007 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sonoma County, California]]\n[[Category:Digital audio distributors]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Online music stores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Music streaming services]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|band practice camps|band camp}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name       = Bandcamp, Inc.\n| logo       = Bandcamp-logotype-color.svg\n| logo_size  = 250px\n| screenshot = \n| type       = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry   = Music streaming, music purchasing\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2008|9|16}}\n| location   = [[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n| founder    = {{Unbulleted list |Ethan Diamond|Shawn Grunberger|Joe Holt|Neal Tucker}}\n| key_people = Ethan Diamond ([[CEO]])<br />Shawn Grunberger ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| alexa = {{DecreasePositive}} 974 ({{as of|2020|2|10|alt=February 2020}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/bandcamp.com |title= Bandcamp.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate= April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| homepage   = {{URL|https://bandcamp.com}}\n}}\n'''Bandcamp''' is an American [[Dot-com company|online]] [[music]] company founded in 2008 by [[Oddpost]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Baio|first= Andy |publisher = Maxy |title= Oddpost Co-Founder Launches Bandcamp, Publishing Platform for Musicians|url= http://waxy.org/2008/09/bandcamp_launch/ |accessdate=28 December 2013|date= Sep 16, 2008}}</ref> co-founder Ethan Diamond and programmers Shawn Grunberger, Joe Holt and Neal Tucker;<ref>{{cite news |last=John|first=Tozzi|title= Helping Indie Musicians Market Their Tunes|url= http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/helping-indie-musicians-market-their-tunes-11172011.html |accessdate=28 December 2013|newspaper=Business Week|date= November 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Private Company Financial Report on Bandcamp, Inc. |publisher= PrivCo |url= http://www.privco.com/private-company/bandcamp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sam|first= Clearman|title=An interview with Joe Holt|url= http://htmltimes.com/band-camp.php | work =The HTML Times|accessdate=28 December 2013 |date= October 1, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Ethan |first= Maffey|title=The Best of Bandcamp: Get in on the ground floor with these sell-it-yourself bands|url=http://www.bendsource.com/bend/the-best-of-bandcamp-get-in-on-the-ground-floor-with-these-sell-it-yourself-bands/Content?oid=2178549| work =The Source Weekly|accessdate=28 December 2013 |date= July 18, 2012 |quote= Web developers and friends Ethan Diamond, Shawn Grunberger, Joe Holt and Neal Tucker launched Bandcamp in 2008}}</ref> the company is headquartered in [[Oakland, California]].<ref name= kqed>{{cite web|accessdate= February 6, 2019|url= https://www.kqed.org/arts/13848866/inside-bandcamp-oakland-online-music-retailers-new-venue-record-shop-and-office|title=Inside Bandcamp's New Oakland Venue, Record Shop and Office|first=Sam |last=Lefebvre|publicationdate=January 17, 2019 |publisher= [[KQED]]|url-status= live |archivedate=May 21, 2019 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20190521010107/https://www.kqed.org/arts/13848866/inside-bandcamp-oakland-online-music-retailers-new-venue-record-shop-and-office}}</ref>\n\n==Model==\nArtists and labels upload music to Bandcamp and control how they sell it, setting their own prices, offering fans the option to pay more <ref>{{cite web |title=Bandcamp Help |url=https://bandcamp.com/help/selling#pricing_performance |website=Bandcamp |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> and selling merchandise.  \n\nFans are able to download their purchases or stream their music on the Bandcamp app/site only once or unlimited times by preserving the purchase voucher. They can also send purchased music as a gift,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.bandcamp.com/2013/11/26/thank-you-its-a-gift/ |title=Thank You, It\u2019s a Gift |work=The Bandcamp Blog |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref> view lyrics, and save individual songs or albums to a wish list. Uploading music to Bandcamp is free, and the company takes a 15% cut of sales made from their website (in addition to [[payment processor|payment processing]] fees), which drops to 10% after an artist's sales surpass $5000.<ref>{{cite news |author=James Shotwell |date=2010-06-20 |title=Bandcamp.com changes business model |publisher=Alt Press |url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/bandcamp.com_changes_business_model/ }}</ref>\n\nDownloads are offered both in [[Lossy audio compression|lossy formats]] as [[MP3]] (320k or V0), [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]] and [[Ogg Vorbis]] and in lossless formats as [[FLAC]], [[Apple Lossless Audio Codec|ALAC]], [[WAV]] and [[AIFF]]. <ref>{{Citation|url=https://get.bandcamp.help/hc/en-us/articles/360009319033-In-which-formats-can-I-download-my-purchases-|title=Bandcamp - In which formats can I download my purchases|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref> In addition to digital downloads artists may offer the purchase of their music on physical media such as [[Audio CD|CD]] or [[Vinyl record|vinyl]].\n\nBandcamp\u2019s website offers users access to an artist\u2019s page featuring information on the artist, social media links, merchandising links and listing their available music. Artists can change the look of their page, and to customize its features.<ref>{{cite web|last=Deitz |first=Ben |url=http://www.switched.com/2011/01/24/bandcamp-review-music-publishing-sharing-site/ |title=Bandcamp Decoded: An Indie Musician's Best (and Most Profitable) Friend |publisher=Switched.com |date=2011-01-24 |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref> In 2010 the site enabled embedded/shared links in other social media sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.bandcamp.com/2010/09/09/full-tracklist-players-facebook-love/ |title=Full Tracklist Players, Facebook Love |publisher=The Bandcamp Blog |date= |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref>\n\n==Notable artists and labels==\nBandcamp gained much attention in July 2010 when [[Amanda Palmer]], Low Places and Bedhed gave up their [[record label]]s and started selling albums on Bandcamp, using [[Twitter]] for promotion.<ref>{{cite news |author=Caroline Klibanoff |date=2010-07-27 |title=Amanda Palmer Brings in $15,000 on Bandcamp in Three Minutes |publisher=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]] |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2010/07/amanda-palmer-sells-15k-on-bandcampin-three-minute.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Glenn Peoples |date=2010-06-22 |title=Amanda Palmer Sells $15K Worth Of Music, Merch In Three Min |publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.biz]] |url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3ic0d7c3a6d02f0164fdfba6f2c15d432c }}</ref>\n\nSeveral [[indie game]] [[List of indie game developers|developers]] published their game soundtracks on Bandcamp,{{when|date=March 2020}} including the creators of ''[[Aquaria (video game)|Aquaria]]'', ''[[Bastion (video game)|Bastion]]'', ''[[Sanctum (2011 video game)|Sanctum]]'', ''[[Machinarium]]'', ''[[Terraria]]'', ''[[Plants vs. Zombies]]'', ''[[Limbo (video game)|Limbo]]'', ''[[Super Meat Boy]]'', ''[[To the Moon]]'', ''[[Fez (video game)|Fez]]'', and ''[[Minecraft]]''.{{importance inline}}\n\nIn December 2014, Bandcamp for Labels was launched. Popular independent labels such as [[Sub Pop]], [[Fat Wreck Chords]], [[Relapse Records]] and [[Epitaph Records]] launched their own Bandcamp pages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riffyou.com/fat-wreck-epitaph-sub-pop-get-bandcamp-pages/ |title=Fat Wreck, Epitaph, Sub-Pop Get Bandcamp Pages |publisher=Riffyou.com |date=December 17, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-18}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Peter Gabriel]] added his complete solo catalog to Bandcamp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/features/peter-gabriel-bandcamp-catalog|title=Peter Gabriel\u2019s Solo Discography Comes to Bandcamp|date=2019-11-15|website=Bandcamp Daily|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==''Bandcamp Daily''==\nIn the summer of 2016, the company launched '''''Bandcamp Daily''''', an online music publication which expanded its editorial content and offers articles about artists on the platform.<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|accessdate=May 20, 2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/20/arts/music/bandcamp-shopping-for-music.html|title=Is Bandcamp the Holy Grail of Online Record Stores?|first=Ben |last=Ratliff|authorlink=Ben Ratliff|publicationdate=August 19, 2016|website=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archivedate=August 19, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819230822/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/20/arts/music/bandcamp-shopping-for-music.html}}</ref><ref name=complex>{{cite web|accessdate=May 21, 2019|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/musicians-earned-270-million-dollars-from-bandcamp-last-year|title=Musicians Earned Over $270 Million From Bandcamp Last Year|first=Tara |last=Mahadevan|publicationdate=February 14, 2018|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|url-status=live|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20190521080822/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/musicians-earned-270-million-dollars-from-bandcamp-last-year}}</ref> The publication is based in New York.<ref name=kqed/> Its managing editor is Jes Skolnik, a writer for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'', as well as former author of [[punk zine]]s.<ref name=glamour>{{cite web|accessdate=May 21, 2019|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/career-late-bloomers|website=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|title=It's OK If You Don't Have Your Career Figured Out by 30|first=Maggie |last=Serota|publicationdate=November 10, 2017|url-status=live|archivedate=November 11, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111012741/https://www.glamour.com/story/career-late-bloomers}}</ref> Among ''Bandcamp Daily'''s columnists there have been writers of ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'',<ref>https://truthout.org/articles/outsourcing-police-investigations-to-google-risks-privacy-and-justice/</ref> ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'',<ref>https://www.inc.com/author/zachary-lipez</ref> [[NPR Music]],<ref>https://www.leafly.com/news/podcasts/subscribe-to-the-hash-podcast-new-season-begins-january-8th</ref> ''Pitchfork''<ref>https://theoutline.com/post/6013/dennis-cooper-very-intriguing-person</ref> and ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''.<ref>https://www.factmag.com/2018/08/08/fact-rated-channel-tres-interview/</ref> \n\nOn August 4, 2017, the staff of ''Bandcamp Daily'' donated all the sales proceeds from the day to the [[Transgender Law Center]], a civil rights organization for [[transgender]] people.<ref name=pitchfork>{{cite web|accessdate=May 21, 2019|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bandcamp-donating-proceeds-to-transgender-law-center-this-friday/|first=Sam|last=Sodomsky|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|publicationdate=July 31, 2017|title=Bandcamp Donating Proceeds to Transgender Law Center This Friday|url-status=live|archivedate=July 31, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731173711/https://pitchfork.com/news/bandcamp-donating-proceeds-to-transgender-law-center-this-friday/}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, the audience of ''Bandcamp Daily'' had increased by 84% since last year.<ref name=complex/><ref name=billboard>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8099603/bandcamp-paid-270-million-musicians-over-2017-review|accessdate=May 20, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=Bandcamp Paid Musicians Over $70M in 2017|publicationdate=February 13, 2018|first=Colin |last=Stutz |url-status=live|archivedate=February 14, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214043954/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8099603/bandcamp-paid-270-million-musicians-over-2017-review}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{citeweb | url = https://daily.bandcamp.com | title = Bandcamp Daily}}\n\n{{Music digital distribution platforms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandcamp}}\n[[Category:2007 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sonoma County, California]]\n[[Category:Digital audio distributors]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Online music stores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Music streaming services]]\n", "name_user": "Intgr", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:REFPUNCT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bandcamp"}
{"title_page": "Fubon Bank (Hong Kong)", "text_new": "{{Use Hong Kong English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Fubon Bank (Hong Kong) Limited <br />\u5bcc\u90a6\u9280\u884c(\u9999\u6e2f)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8\n| logo = Fubon Bank Logo.png\n| logo_caption = \n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = [[Sun Hung Kai Finance Company]]<br/>[[Sun Hung Kai Bank]] (1982)<br />International Bank of Asia (1986)\n| location = {{HKG}}|\n| former type = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = [[Banking]]\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = \n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = \n| location_country = [[Hong Kong]]\n| locations = <!-- Number of -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only for financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Fubon Financial Holding Co., Ltd.]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = [http://www.fubonbank.com.hk/web/html/index_e.html www.fubonbank.com.hk]\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n| bodystyle = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|order=jp\n|showflag=stp\n|s=\u5bcc\u90a6\u94f6\u884c(\u9999\u6e2f)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8\n|t=\u5bcc\u90a6\u9280\u884c(\u9999\u6e2f)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8\n|j=fu<sup>3</sup> bong<sup>1</sup> ngan<sup>4</sup> hong<sup>4</sup> (hoeng<sup>1</sup> gong<sup>2</sup>) jau<sup>5</sup> haan<sup>6</sup> gung<sup>1</sup> si<sup>1</sup>\n|y=Fub\u014dng Ng\u00e0hnh\u00f2hng (H\u0113ungg\u00f3ng) Yauhhaahng\u016bngs\u012b\n|p=F\u00f9b\u0101ng Y\u00ednh\u00e1ng (Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng) Y\u01d2uxi\u00e0ng\u014dngs\u012b\n}}\n'''Fubon Bank (Hong Kong) Limited (\u201cFubon Bank\u201d)'''  is a wholly owned subsidiary of Fubon Financial Holding Co., Ltd. (\u201cFubon Financial Holdings\u201d), one of the largest financial holding companies in Taiwan. Fubon Financial Holdings is now the only Taiwanese financial institution with banking subsidiaries in China, Taiwan and Hong Kong. Fubon Bank operates 19 branches and 1 Securities Services Centre in Hong Kong, providing a wide range of financial services encompassing consumer and wholesale banking, wealth management, financial markets, securities brokerage and investment services. Fubon Bank holds an A-2 short-term, BBB+ long-term rating from Standard & Poor\u2019s. The rating reflects Fubon Bank\u2019s strong capitalization, good liquidity and sound asset quality.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fubon Bank (Hong Kong)}}\n*[http://www.fubonbank.com.hk/web/html/index_e.html Fubon Bank (Hong Kong) Limited (\u201cFubon Bank\u201d)]\n*[http://www.taipeifubon.com.tw/ Fubon Financial Holding Co., Ltd.]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Hong Kong English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Fubon Bank (Hong Kong) Limited <br />\u5bcc\u90a6\u9280\u884c(\u9999\u6e2f)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8\n| logo = Fubon Bank Logo.png\n| logo_caption = \n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = [[Sun Hung Kai Finance Company]]<br/>[[Sun Hung Kai Bank]] (1982)<br />International Bank of Asia (1986)\n| location = {{HKG}}|\n| former type = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = [[Banking]]\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = \n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = \n| location_country = [[Hong Kong]]\n| locations = <!-- Number of -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only for financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Fubon Financial Holding Co., Ltd.]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = [http://www.fubonbank.com.hk/web/html/index_e.html fubonbank.com.hk]\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n| bodystyle = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|order=jp\n|showflag=stp\n|s=\u5bcc\u90a6\u94f6\u884c(\u9999\u6e2f)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8\n|t=\u5bcc\u90a6\u9280\u884c(\u9999\u6e2f)\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8\n|j=fu<sup>3</sup> bong<sup>1</sup> ngan<sup>4</sup> hong<sup>4</sup> (hoeng<sup>1</sup> gong<sup>2</sup>) jau<sup>5</sup> haan<sup>6</sup> gung<sup>1</sup> si<sup>1</sup>\n|y=Fub\u014dng Ng\u00e0hnh\u00f2hng (H\u0113ungg\u00f3ng) Yauhhaahng\u016bngs\u012b\n|p=F\u00f9b\u0101ng Y\u00ednh\u00e1ng (Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng) Y\u01d2uxi\u00e0ng\u014dngs\u012b\n}}\n'''Fubon Bank (Hong Kong) Limited (\u201cFubon Bank\u201d)'''  is a wholly owned subsidiary of Fubon Financial Holding Co., Ltd. (\u201cFubon Financial Holdings\u201d), one of the largest financial holding companies in Taiwan. Fubon Financial Holdings is now the only Taiwanese financial institution with banking subsidiaries in China, Taiwan and Hong Kong. Fubon Bank operates 19 branches and 1 Securities Services Centre in Hong Kong, providing a wide range of financial services encompassing consumer and wholesale banking, wealth management, financial markets, securities brokerage and investment services. Fubon Bank holds an A-2 short-term, BBB+ long-term rating from Standard & Poor\u2019s. The rating reflects Fubon Bank\u2019s strong capitalization, good liquidity and sound asset quality.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fubon Bank (Hong Kong)}}\n*[http://www.fubonbank.com.hk/web/html/index_e.html Fubon Bank (Hong Kong) Limited (\u201cFubon Bank\u201d)]\n*[http://www.taipeifubon.com.tw/ Fubon Financial Holding Co., Ltd.]\n", "name_user": "Fubon2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "edit website url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fubon_Bank_(Hong_Kong)"}
